WEBVTT

00:00:00.190 --> 00:00:00.990
Cool.

00:00:00.990 --> 00:00:03.690
Thank you.

00:00:03.840 --> 00:00:04.650
Thanks so much for coming.

00:00:04.920 --> 00:00:05.120
Hi.

00:00:05.120 --> 00:00:07.340
I'm Mary.

00:00:07.490 --> 00:00:12.980
I'm here all the way from Orangery land,

00:00:12.980 --> 00:00:16.560
so-called Melbourne, Australia.

00:00:16.560 --> 00:00:18.240
I'm one of the creators of Roomy.

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:24.060
That's an at-proto-based group chat app

00:00:24.060 --> 00:00:26.940
for communities.

00:00:27.090 --> 00:00:30.060
I'm a guest here on this beautiful land which is un

00:00:30.060 --> 00:00:33.230
ceded ancestral territory of Musqueam people.

00:00:33.330 --> 00:00:40.910
I want to extend my respect to them and to all indigenous

00:00:40.910 --> 00:00:46.000
people around the world who are protecting life from life and communal

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.480
cultures on this planet against colonial destruction.

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:55.620
I guess if I had to sum up what I really want

00:00:55.700 --> 00:01:00.440
to say, it's that communities are critically important and poorly

00:01:00.470 --> 00:01:06.420
understood and most of our tech is very individual-oriented and

00:01:06.420 --> 00:01:10.640
that understanding how communities work, especially the role of organisers

00:01:10.820 --> 00:01:17.900
and in particular when that community is about cooperating and coordinating

00:01:17.900 --> 00:01:19.860
to achieve something.

00:01:20.390 --> 00:01:24.450
If we can understand that, we can better understand how social

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:26.400
systems change more broadly.

00:01:26.620 --> 00:01:32.740
And with that, I also just want to thank the organis

00:01:32.740 --> 00:01:35.690
ers of this conference for bringing this event together.

00:01:35.690 --> 00:01:36.720
It's a massive job.

00:01:39.810 --> 00:01:42.870
I also personally really need to acknowledge this book which has just

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:46.490
like had a really enormous impact on my thinking.

00:01:46.490 --> 00:01:51.030
It draws on a lot of different thinkers on the topic of

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:57.330
civilizational transition away from our capitalist, colonial, developmental

00:01:57.420 --> 00:02:00.160
ist, extractive society and crisis.

00:02:01.950 --> 00:02:06.490
It draws on critical thought and practice across disciplines and particularly from

00:02:06.640 --> 00:02:10.540
indigenous and other communal cultures in the global south and especially in

00:02:10.680 --> 00:02:15.200
Latin America with the goal of articulating an approach for design

00:02:15.200 --> 00:02:15.440
.

00:02:15.440 --> 00:02:19.760
And by design, I mean if we need a civiliz

00:02:19.760 --> 00:02:25.090
ational transition, what are we transitioning to?

00:02:25.100 --> 00:02:26.310
Who gets to decide?

00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:33.190
If our current civilisation is one that systematically destroys communal cultures

00:02:33.200 --> 00:02:37.840
, how can we design one with the conditions for communal life

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:43.360
to flourish and where cultures can practice the design of themselves?

00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:46.720
That's my North Star.

00:02:50.580 --> 00:02:52.380
Roomie is what we've been working on.

00:02:52.380 --> 00:02:56.320
It's a tool for communities to chat, stay connected,

00:02:56.320 --> 00:02:58.010
work on things together.

00:02:58.010 --> 00:03:03.190
When I first got involved, I wasn't necessarily thinking that

00:03:03.290 --> 00:03:07.830
another chat app was what communities really need right now.

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:11.180
But one of my co-founders, Ellen, had

00:03:11.350 --> 00:03:16.770
written up this idea that I found compelling, which is that

00:03:17.110 --> 00:03:20.800
group chat is minimum viable community.

00:03:20.870 --> 00:03:26.390
Or in other words, chat can be the basic foundation for

00:03:26.410 --> 00:03:28.550
communities to connect online.

00:03:28.690 --> 00:03:33.280
There are so many things that we could and should be building

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:35.430
, but chat is where we start.

00:03:35.460 --> 00:03:42.060
Anyone with internet access is familiar at some level with the UX

00:03:42.060 --> 00:03:44.670
metaphor of the UX metaphor of a chat room to mean a

00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:49.540
specific context for communication between specific people.

00:03:49.540 --> 00:03:52.530
You can absolutely do community in a chat room.

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:59.320
My partner and I had a baby in 2021 and at the

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:01.680
time we weren't, we weren't close with any other

00:04:01.680 --> 00:04:02.400
queer parents.

00:04:02.410 --> 00:04:05.670
And before I go on, I couldn't be here without

00:04:05.760 --> 00:04:09.100
my partner holding the floor while I'm away.

00:04:09.100 --> 00:04:11.850
So, thank you, Asia and all the carers who

00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:14.320
make our connection here possible.

00:04:14.510 --> 00:04:21.950
Becoming a parent can be isolating in a similar way to

00:04:21.950 --> 00:04:24.400
how coming out as queer can be isolating.

00:04:24.580 --> 00:04:26.160
And it was scary.

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:30.800
But people put us in touch with other friends in the community

00:04:30.800 --> 00:04:34.950
having kids and we started a signal group chat that has honestly

00:04:35.160 --> 00:04:36.560
been a lifeline sometimes.

00:04:36.750 --> 00:04:42.880
We try to practice mutual aid and show up for each other

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:42.880
.

00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:47.360
We organize to bring meals when someone just gave birth or is

00:04:47.360 --> 00:04:47.760
unwell.

00:04:47.940 --> 00:04:51.280
We share advice and emotional support.

00:04:53.450 --> 00:04:54.310
It's just a group chat.

00:04:54.330 --> 00:04:58.320
But that shared context lets us do community.

00:04:58.490 --> 00:05:01.440
It's simple, but it's precious.

00:05:08.550 --> 00:05:10.550
What happens when the needs of communities get more complex?

00:05:10.750 --> 00:05:19.680
My drawings are a bit messed up.

00:05:19.870 --> 00:05:26.420
Six years ago, my friends got me interested in a project

00:05:26.420 --> 00:05:26.640
.

00:05:26.820 --> 00:05:31.290
They wanted to make a website with a calendar for activists and

00:05:31.500 --> 00:05:33.120
community organizers.

00:05:33.290 --> 00:05:38.300
We'll all just keep it updated each week and with whatever

00:05:38.410 --> 00:05:40.510
we're seeing out in the world.

00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:43.860
And I didn't really know how to make web apps at

00:05:43.860 --> 00:05:44.560
the time.

00:05:44.740 --> 00:05:48.030
But somehow that didn't stop me from saying, what if

00:05:48.130 --> 00:05:49.210
we made a web app?

00:05:52.020 --> 00:05:55.480
What if we gave organizers the tools to publish what they're

00:05:55.480 --> 00:05:55.920
doing?

00:05:56.100 --> 00:06:00.530
And we created a map of all the different parts of our

00:06:00.800 --> 00:06:02.960
entire social movement.

00:06:03.140 --> 00:06:09.920
And create new ways for people to connect with existing groups and

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:14.720
for different groups to work together and share resources all around the

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:15.360
world.

00:06:21.330 --> 00:06:23.390
I guess you could say that at the time, I didn

00:06:23.390 --> 00:06:25.760
't really understand the value of taking small steps.

00:06:25.930 --> 00:06:32.080
We absolutely should have started by just manually updating a calendar.

00:06:32.270 --> 00:06:40.340
Fast forward five years and I, by total chance,

00:06:40.340 --> 00:06:42.640
stumble across these guys, Ellen and Ziklag.

00:06:42.820 --> 00:06:47.440
And they had this old motto, find the others.

00:06:51.450 --> 00:06:56.800
We had both independently spent the last few years trying to build

00:06:56.800 --> 00:06:59.920
community scale social apps using matrix protocol.

00:07:00.140 --> 00:07:01.840
Given up on that.

00:07:02.010 --> 00:07:04.880
And started on a local first web publishing app.

00:07:05.030 --> 00:07:08.630
We both had strong visions for what tech that puts users and

00:07:08.680 --> 00:07:10.640
communities first should look like.

00:07:12.060 --> 00:07:14.070
And we had both learned the hard way, the importance of

00:07:14.070 --> 00:07:15.030
taking small steps.

00:07:15.190 --> 00:07:21.030
We were both thinking about how collective resource sharing can defeat monopoly

00:07:21.030 --> 00:07:21.920
network effects.

00:07:22.090 --> 00:07:26.530
We were both wondering what gets us in good loops to create

00:07:26.870 --> 00:07:28.160
good systems.

00:07:30.010 --> 00:07:33.210
And we happened to live in Melbourne, Oslo, Arkansas

00:07:33.280 --> 00:07:33.520
.

00:07:33.700 --> 00:07:37.440
We met in a group chat.

00:07:37.660 --> 00:07:41.840
Sorry, there's more on the slide.

00:07:41.990 --> 00:07:44.550
We found each other in a group chat.

00:07:44.730 --> 00:07:48.770
The hypothesis that chat is minimum viable community is what led the

00:07:48.870 --> 00:07:51.930
three of us and the whole crew of other people to spend

00:07:51.930 --> 00:07:54.080
the last year focused on Roomie.

00:07:54.230 --> 00:07:58.680
So what happens when the needs of communities get more complex?

00:07:58.980 --> 00:08:01.910
Like I said before, the core of a chat room is

00:08:02.050 --> 00:08:02.960
shared context.

00:08:03.130 --> 00:08:06.040
Add more voices into the mix and we start to lose track

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:06.950
of context.

00:08:07.140 --> 00:08:11.360
And we've seen that organizing into channels and threads works.

00:08:11.510 --> 00:08:14.470
So these are in Roomie available to use now.

00:08:14.630 --> 00:08:18.160
We call the big shared community context a space.

00:08:20.010 --> 00:08:23.110
If you haven't checked it out, this is the atmosphere

00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:23.910
conf Roomie space.

00:08:24.150 --> 00:08:29.200
So channels are on the side and they're in categories.

00:08:29.350 --> 00:08:32.670
If you open a channel, you can see recent threads.

00:08:32.900 --> 00:08:38.720
We have reactions, replies, chat stuff.

00:08:38.890 --> 00:08:41.340
And if you're an admin, you can move messages into

00:08:41.340 --> 00:08:41.840
a thread.

00:08:41.990 --> 00:08:46.000
If you want to retroactively introduce some more structure and organization

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:46.000
.

00:08:47.940 --> 00:08:51.110
Roomie is not the first open source group chat app that

00:08:51.200 --> 00:08:52.480
has these features.

00:08:52.630 --> 00:08:54.320
And there's still a lot of rough edges.

00:08:54.500 --> 00:08:58.490
But the difference is that I -- the difference is that Room

00:08:58.490 --> 00:08:59.500
ie is an @proto app.

00:09:04.660 --> 00:09:07.950
With this caveat, messages aren't on the PDS because

00:09:07.950 --> 00:09:11.040
we want to launch private spaces ASAP.

00:09:11.220 --> 00:09:15.200
They live on our equivalent of a PDS called leaf.

00:09:15.380 --> 00:09:20.720
It has a DID you can control to adversarially migrate

00:09:20.720 --> 00:09:23.430
it to your own self-hosted leaf server.

00:09:24.340 --> 00:09:28.120
The data is formatted just like app proto records and you

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:31.120
can build an alternative client too.

00:09:31.290 --> 00:09:33.200
Auth is just an app proto service token.

00:09:33.380 --> 00:09:38.250
All of which is to say we care about credible exit and

00:09:38.250 --> 00:09:39.120
interop.

00:09:41.850 --> 00:09:44.740
And with permission spaces on the horizon, we're going to

00:09:44.740 --> 00:09:47.280
keep working to make interop as easy as possible.

00:09:47.400 --> 00:09:49.360
And we're really excited about what that's going to unlock

00:09:49.360 --> 00:09:49.360
.

00:09:49.550 --> 00:09:54.490
Because users deserve easy access to their data on whatever app they

00:09:54.490 --> 00:09:55.200
want.

00:09:59.250 --> 00:10:02.270
A lot of communities currently have a home on Discord, including

00:10:02.270 --> 00:10:03.520
us, when we're working on this.

00:10:03.700 --> 00:10:10.860
Most communities want to try out and progressively move to using Room

00:10:11.010 --> 00:10:13.680
ie without losing users in the process.

00:10:13.900 --> 00:10:18.720
So, I built a Discord Roomie bridge this year.

00:10:18.890 --> 00:10:22.570
And we started contacting the first few communities to test it out

00:10:22.570 --> 00:10:22.710
.

00:10:26.260 --> 00:10:27.760
This is the Roomie space.

00:10:27.940 --> 00:10:30.480
Showing Roomie messages.

00:10:30.660 --> 00:10:33.830
Interwoven with bridged Discord messages.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:35.830
You can see them with a little badge.

00:10:36.030 --> 00:10:42.270
So, you can be on either side of the platform and

00:10:42.290 --> 00:10:43.360
just communicate like normal.

00:10:43.550 --> 00:10:49.040
You might have also noticed that we're bridging in messages

00:10:49.040 --> 00:10:50.880
from the stream place chat.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.950
So, when the stream ends for this talk, the chat

00:10:53.980 --> 00:10:56.640
in the stream should also appear in Roomie.

00:10:56.810 --> 00:10:59.200
AtProto makes that easy.

00:10:59.390 --> 00:11:06.990
Tom Scanlan, who's building OpenMeet, also

00:11:06.990 --> 00:11:09.360
built this AtProto calendar viewer into Roomie.

00:11:09.540 --> 00:11:13.350
So, these are standard, like, community.

00:11:13.490 --> 00:11:16.000
lexicon events for the conference.

00:11:16.170 --> 00:11:17.860
They're published by atmosphereconf.

00:11:17.870 --> 00:11:18.080
org.

00:11:19.950 --> 00:11:22.240
It's the same events you can see on the Conf website

00:11:22.250 --> 00:11:27.540
and other calendar viewers, like Flowbits, atmo.

00:11:27.540 --> 00:11:28.400
rsvp.

00:11:28.580 --> 00:11:31.750
Shout out to Flowbit, who's, like, done

00:11:31.840 --> 00:11:33.050
heaps of work on Roomie as well.

00:11:33.290 --> 00:11:35.750
Like, incredible UI work.

00:11:35.910 --> 00:11:38.160
We could take this so much further.

00:11:40.570 --> 00:11:43.520
But that's just a taste of what we've been building

00:11:43.640 --> 00:11:45.010
so far with Roomie.

00:11:45.300 --> 00:11:49.570
Less control to apps means users are more free and we can

00:11:49.570 --> 00:11:51.280
build cool stuff.

00:11:54.070 --> 00:11:56.550
The whole point of social software is interconnecting.

00:11:56.710 --> 00:12:00.480
AtProto lets us do that while meaningfully giving more

00:12:00.480 --> 00:12:05.280
control to users and, to some extent, communities.

00:12:08.250 --> 00:12:10.710
At the start of this talk, I said, communities are

00:12:11.030 --> 00:12:15.060
critically important and poorly understood, but most of our tech is

00:12:15.060 --> 00:12:16.480
made with individuals in mind.

00:12:16.650 --> 00:12:21.670
AtProto was designed for big world social networking, where

00:12:21.680 --> 00:12:25.690
individuals publish data for broadcasting across the whole network to be aggreg

00:12:26.130 --> 00:12:27.670
ated and consumed.

00:12:29.450 --> 00:12:30.230
Just a name and shame.

00:12:30.430 --> 00:12:36.590
But communities need to be somewhat separate, protected from the big

00:12:36.870 --> 00:12:38.310
world to really flourish.

00:12:38.660 --> 00:12:42.170
Like I said before, the essence of a chat room is

00:12:42.170 --> 00:12:43.690
shared context.

00:12:43.940 --> 00:12:48.130
When we can reliably establish shared context, shared norms, we

00:12:48.130 --> 00:12:51.710
can speak more freely, trust each other more easily, and

00:12:51.710 --> 00:12:52.800
get more stuff done together.

00:12:56.410 --> 00:12:58.330
Okay, so, I mean, we live in an individual

00:12:58.340 --> 00:13:00.160
ising, often isolating world.

00:13:00.310 --> 00:13:03.280
And sometimes it feels like there is no alternative, nothing outside

00:13:03.380 --> 00:13:03.840
of that.

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:06.400
How do we enter the communal?

00:13:06.580 --> 00:13:11.050
What happens in the inter-tidal zone between the big

00:13:11.350 --> 00:13:13.740
world and the protected space?

00:13:14.020 --> 00:13:18.240
The late union organiser, Jane McAulvey,

00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:23.670
made some useful distinctions for the different levels of agency in

00:13:23.930 --> 00:13:24.560
collective action.

00:13:25.900 --> 00:13:26.480
You can donate.

00:13:26.480 --> 00:13:26.480
You can donate.

00:13:26.660 --> 00:13:30.640
You could be advocating for an issue.

00:13:30.820 --> 00:13:35.850
You can be mobilising people, and mobilising means you

00:13:35.970 --> 00:13:37.600
don't just want to inform people.

00:13:37.750 --> 00:13:39.840
You want other people to get up and do something.

00:13:40.020 --> 00:13:44.440
And when I think about how broadcast-based social media can

00:13:44.790 --> 00:13:47.600
help social movements, I think about mobilising.

00:13:49.930 --> 00:13:52.440
You can mobilise a car, but what good is that

00:13:52.440 --> 00:13:55.250
if you don't know where you're going to drive it

00:13:55.250 --> 00:13:55.600
?

00:13:57.200 --> 00:14:00.390
So, collectivity is made by organisers.

00:14:00.670 --> 00:14:06.910
Organising is about empowering other people to have agency within the

00:14:07.110 --> 00:14:09.690
frame of your shared work or shared problem.

00:14:13.910 --> 00:14:15.600
It's an evergreen meme.

00:14:15.780 --> 00:14:20.480
Union organising is all about building collective people power.

00:14:20.660 --> 00:14:22.160
Or fish power.

00:14:22.350 --> 00:14:28.580
Each of us on our own might have pretty limited leverage in

00:14:28.790 --> 00:14:30.000
whatever problem we're facing.

00:14:30.810 --> 00:14:33.320
But when a lot of us, with our limited leverage,

00:14:33.510 --> 00:14:37.440
choose to cooperate, we can collectively get big leverage.

00:14:37.590 --> 00:14:38.560
That's the theory of change.

00:14:42.660 --> 00:14:47.520
Organisers need tools that help communities create, refine,

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:51.820
and communicate an effective mental model of the system that they're

00:14:51.820 --> 00:14:53.350
trying to gain leverage in.

00:14:53.530 --> 00:14:56.730
We want Rumi to be that tool, where it's

00:14:56.800 --> 00:15:01.150
not just about keeping the chat going, but reflexively going

00:15:01.150 --> 00:15:05.240
back through the chat to strip out the noise and keep the

00:15:05.250 --> 00:15:06.460
key insights.

00:15:09.060 --> 00:15:13.840
Putting messages into threads, letting threads become the seeds for refined

00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:18.470
documents, potentially even publishing those documents for wider distribution.

00:15:18.660 --> 00:15:23.600
Maybe sharing the key insights with other groups, other communities to

00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:26.470
coordinate and to find the others.

00:15:26.730 --> 00:15:30.030
The public at Proto Social Graph can really help us with

00:15:30.130 --> 00:15:32.480
these points of interconnection.

00:15:32.660 --> 00:15:38.720
So, the rest of this talk is like a vision board

00:15:38.720 --> 00:15:38.720
.

00:15:39.060 --> 00:15:40.400
For what comes next.

00:15:40.580 --> 00:15:45.470
One thing we want to build is a bit like web rings

00:15:45.470 --> 00:15:46.480
between communities.

00:15:46.700 --> 00:15:52.100
Like, honestly, bring this back.

00:15:52.340 --> 00:15:57.210
Web rings are a really cute practice back from the web 1

00:15:57.210 --> 00:15:57.340
.

00:15:57.460 --> 00:15:58.400
0 days.

00:15:58.580 --> 00:16:02.730
People would form a network of personal sites by linking to each

00:16:02.730 --> 00:16:03.580
other in a ring.

00:16:05.080 --> 00:16:07.650
So, you keep clicking next and you loop around back to

00:16:07.830 --> 00:16:08.560
the same site.

00:16:08.740 --> 00:16:11.180
For us, I'm not sure if it should be in

00:16:11.180 --> 00:16:14.400
a ring, but we do really want to see how distinct

00:16:14.730 --> 00:16:18.830
communities that are aligned in some way can interconnect without having to

00:16:18.930 --> 00:16:19.920
form a hierarchy.

00:16:25.830 --> 00:16:26.710
So, I'm going to tell a story.

00:16:26.910 --> 00:16:31.910
About a decade ago, I got involved in an environmental campaign

00:16:31.920 --> 00:16:33.280
called Stop Adani.

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:37.260
Adani is a mining company that was trying to build the

00:16:37.260 --> 00:16:39.600
biggest coal mine in the southern hemisphere.

00:16:40.490 --> 00:16:43.360
And our government was funding them to do it.

00:16:43.540 --> 00:16:51.230
I just hated the total inaction on climate change and needed

00:16:51.230 --> 00:16:52.960
to do something about it.

00:16:53.110 --> 00:16:57.120
So, this ended up being my introduction to direct action,

00:16:57.120 --> 00:17:00.240
which is where you go and put your body on the line

00:17:00.240 --> 00:17:03.500
, trying to stand directly in the way of something that a

00:17:03.500 --> 00:17:05.760
just society wouldn't tolerate.

00:17:05.950 --> 00:17:12.800
When I got up to the camp, everyone was practicing consensus

00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:16.230
-based decision-making with this idea that we don't

00:17:16.230 --> 00:17:18.650
pressure or coerce anyone to be part of an action

00:17:18.800 --> 00:17:18.950
.

00:17:19.190 --> 00:17:23.200
We're working towards collective consent for whatever we do.

00:17:23.290 --> 00:17:28.410
I started getting skilled up in facilitating meetings to learn how to

00:17:28.460 --> 00:17:32.310
make that happen with a big group of people efficiently.

00:17:32.500 --> 00:17:35.790
And being part of this practice really changed me.

00:17:39.510 --> 00:17:42.240
I also learned that we had a few strategic goals.

00:17:42.420 --> 00:17:46.230
But our main focus was to show investors that the project was

00:17:46.370 --> 00:17:47.430
unreliable.

00:17:47.620 --> 00:17:53.060
To do that, we needed to identify choke points in their

00:17:53.110 --> 00:17:56.920
system and their process and work out ways to exploit them and

00:17:56.920 --> 00:17:59.740
blow out their costs while minimizing our own.

00:17:59.860 --> 00:18:05.180
I've participated to different degrees in a lot of actions and

00:18:05.180 --> 00:18:07.920
campaigns since then with ups and downs.

00:18:08.090 --> 00:18:11.270
But I think that campaign was where I really got a sense

00:18:11.360 --> 00:18:14.310
of how much is involved to organize on that scale.

00:18:14.510 --> 00:18:20.560
Ultimately, the mine did go ahead, but it was only

00:18:20.560 --> 00:18:22.800
a sixth of the scale that they'd proposed.

00:18:22.950 --> 00:18:25.840
And the primary reason is they couldn't attract the capital.

00:18:26.020 --> 00:18:31.050
So this is a review of the secondary targets to the campaign

00:18:31.110 --> 00:18:37.910
, including financiers and how many of them publicly ruled out

00:18:38.050 --> 00:18:39.920
supporting the mine.

00:18:40.100 --> 00:18:45.410
In the commons analysis in 2022, the mine had been

00:18:45.420 --> 00:18:46.480
delayed by nine years.

00:18:46.660 --> 00:18:51.130
And the primary tactic they identified used by groups active in the

00:18:51.420 --> 00:18:53.120
campaign was information sharing.

00:18:56.070 --> 00:18:58.970
So I came in to stop Adani in a relatively brief

00:18:58.970 --> 00:19:00.480
and limited capacity.

00:19:00.660 --> 00:19:04.230
And I learned that what we were doing was just a small

00:19:04.280 --> 00:19:06.640
part of a much bigger system.

00:19:06.820 --> 00:19:11.290
There were non-profits doing campaign research, strategic litigation.

00:19:11.620 --> 00:19:14.910
There was volunteer community groups doing public campaigning.

00:19:15.140 --> 00:19:18.650
There was a Wangan and Jagalingu traditional owners group

00:19:18.760 --> 00:19:19.440
opposing the mine.

00:19:20.100 --> 00:19:23.040
We had links with groups based in student unions around the country

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:23.040
.

00:19:23.220 --> 00:19:27.200
And all of these were like different communities that were all coordinating

00:19:27.200 --> 00:19:30.550
with each other and supporting each other with no hierarchy.

00:19:30.660 --> 00:19:34.550
I only got a little sense of how much overhead went into

00:19:34.690 --> 00:19:35.520
that coordination.

00:19:35.690 --> 00:19:37.690
But I'm going to say it was a lot of very

00:19:37.690 --> 00:19:41.440
thankless admin that is also critical organizing work.

00:19:43.740 --> 00:19:46.720
But I hope with this example, you can imagine a future

00:19:46.840 --> 00:19:50.990
or a version of this reality where you could have the Brisbane

00:19:50.990 --> 00:19:54.230
chapter of the non-profit, which is all volunteers,

00:19:54.230 --> 00:19:57.910
and the Sydney chapter, and the funded national group, and

00:19:57.920 --> 00:20:03.060
a group for lawyers against Adani, the traditional owners group

00:20:03.160 --> 00:20:06.410
, and the direct action camp, probably being pretty quiet until

00:20:06.410 --> 00:20:08.070
we get end-to-end encryption.

00:20:09.200 --> 00:20:13.850
And these are all autonomous community spaces accessed with Rumi or

00:20:13.990 --> 00:20:15.120
whatever client makes sense.

00:20:15.290 --> 00:20:18.050
And none of them have to own each other, but they

00:20:18.050 --> 00:20:21.360
can express something about the relationship with each other in their UI

00:20:21.360 --> 00:20:23.370
and their access control settings.

00:20:23.620 --> 00:20:29.360
All of these groups want and need to be autonomous, and

00:20:29.360 --> 00:20:31.760
they also want and need to collaborate.

00:20:31.940 --> 00:20:36.080
The current solutions force us to choose between the two.

00:20:39.190 --> 00:20:41.730
So, to be clear, I'm not just trying to

00:20:41.960 --> 00:20:43.520
say hierarchy is bad.

00:20:43.700 --> 00:20:50.000
Big communities often naturally have concentric rings of values and mission

00:20:50.150 --> 00:20:53.210
alignment, experience, capacity to lead and act as an organizer

00:20:53.210 --> 00:20:57.520
, and that's why we see hierarchical role-based

00:20:57.530 --> 00:21:00.160
moderation, for example, working pretty well for a lot of

00:21:00.160 --> 00:21:01.270
online communities.

00:21:04.480 --> 00:21:05.920
It shouldn't necessarily be the default.

00:21:06.110 --> 00:21:11.320
Yesterday, Blaine mentioned Nathan Schneider's concept of implicit

00:21:11.320 --> 00:21:14.370
feudalism, and my thinking is that we can avoid

00:21:14.710 --> 00:21:18.560
that by creating tools that empower users to step into governance,

00:21:18.730 --> 00:21:19.410
into organizing.

00:21:19.660 --> 00:21:25.720
If people know Eleanor Ostrom, Governing the

00:21:26.070 --> 00:21:29.280
Commons, one of my key takeaways from that was the ability

00:21:29.290 --> 00:21:33.240
to participate in modifying rules is one of the principles of successful

00:21:33.270 --> 00:21:35.680
commons governance.

00:21:35.850 --> 00:21:39.890
In apps like Rumi, where a space can have many

00:21:39.930 --> 00:21:43.810
channels or other structures, some of them might be private or

00:21:43.810 --> 00:21:46.240
have different access boundaries.

00:21:46.420 --> 00:21:51.280
That structure can become complex in a way that's culturally integral

00:21:51.280 --> 00:21:51.430
.

00:21:53.470 --> 00:21:55.760
We don't want that structure bound to any one app,

00:21:55.760 --> 00:21:58.460
so I think that's just like something to think about as

00:21:58.510 --> 00:22:01.110
we move into permissioned spaces world.

00:22:01.300 --> 00:22:05.600
How can we make governance structures interoperable?

00:22:05.790 --> 00:22:13.990
Just to keep expanding the vision board, maybe there are

00:22:14.340 --> 00:22:19.210
some citizen scientists using a separate app on Atproto where

00:22:19.220 --> 00:22:22.640
you can record observations of endangered species.

00:22:22.830 --> 00:22:28.050
And at the same time, the lawyers against Adani are

00:22:28.050 --> 00:22:31.670
trying to mount an environmental regulation case against the mine, and

00:22:31.670 --> 00:22:36.610
they have a feed set up where they can track observations of

00:22:36.610 --> 00:22:40.490
the black-throated finch, the yakka

00:22:40.640 --> 00:22:45.420
skink, the ornamental snake, within the specific region

00:22:45.420 --> 00:22:46.560
affected by the mine.

00:22:46.740 --> 00:22:51.770
And they're all showing up automatically in their space as usable

00:22:51.890 --> 00:22:52.550
evidence.

00:22:52.740 --> 00:22:57.210
The UI for rendering that data could be a plugin, someone

00:22:57.440 --> 00:23:00.620
published on Atproto, maybe like a web tile or

00:23:00.620 --> 00:23:04.600
an inlay component, and the lawyers can choose how they

00:23:04.600 --> 00:23:05.280
want it rendered.

00:23:05.460 --> 00:23:11.120
Soon there's a new space for organising citizen scientists in

00:23:11.120 --> 00:23:15.670
the area to all travel out to the field together, specifically

00:23:15.800 --> 00:23:18.480
to gather observations to benefit the legal case.

00:23:18.630 --> 00:23:24.190
So open social means the opportunities for people everywhere to coordinate and

00:23:24.190 --> 00:23:27.200
get aligned on things we care about can just explode.

00:23:37.880 --> 00:23:40.390
I wanted to talk about a climate-related campaign because the

00:23:40.710 --> 00:23:44.180
climate movement is full of really smart people who have gotten good

00:23:44.180 --> 00:23:45.360
at system modelling.

00:23:45.550 --> 00:23:48.710
Weather systems, sure.

00:23:48.800 --> 00:23:50.880
Ecologies, yes.

00:23:50.880 --> 00:23:55.790
But also working out how to coordinate and align incentives between really

00:23:55.790 --> 00:24:00.800
diverse actors, states, market actors, non-profits,

00:24:00.800 --> 00:24:02.220
community groups around the whole world.

00:24:02.420 --> 00:24:05.910
What we're doing with the open social web is really similar

00:24:05.910 --> 00:24:06.890
in a lot of ways.

00:24:07.300 --> 00:24:12.710
Monopoly control of global communications infrastructure is also a planetary problem

00:24:12.710 --> 00:24:12.720
.

00:24:12.890 --> 00:24:16.920
And we've been stuck in reinforcing feedback loops causing so much

00:24:16.920 --> 00:24:17.840
destruction.

00:24:18.060 --> 00:24:23.680
Consider the effort with which fossil fuel companies have tried to prevent

00:24:24.430 --> 00:24:27.710
increasingly cheap renewable energy from entering the market and cutting into their

00:24:27.810 --> 00:24:28.160
profits.

00:24:28.340 --> 00:24:33.910
Like renewable energy, the benefits of everyone having control over their

00:24:33.920 --> 00:24:37.130
data will be obvious to everyone once you break out of the

00:24:37.130 --> 00:24:38.240
monopoly feedback loop.

00:24:39.800 --> 00:24:40.960
And there's no question that we will.

00:24:41.140 --> 00:24:46.060
As I finish up, I just want to come back to

00:24:46.060 --> 00:24:50.000
this question from Designs for the Pluriverse.

00:24:50.170 --> 00:24:53.280
What does it mean to design a civilisation in which communal

00:24:53.280 --> 00:24:57.280
life can flourish and communities can practise the design of themselves?

00:24:57.460 --> 00:25:03.970
The author argues that the concept of autonomy, like self-

00:25:03.970 --> 00:25:06.800
determination, is a keystone in decolonial Latin

00:25:06.800 --> 00:25:11.120
American thought that could shape how we answer that question.

00:25:11.270 --> 00:25:14.320
He proposes a framework called autonomous design.

00:25:14.490 --> 00:25:19.750
I'd like to go into it more, but I'm

00:25:19.750 --> 00:25:21.710
going to just wrap up now.

00:25:21.910 --> 00:25:23.680
But I'd love to talk about this with anyone.

00:25:34.720 --> 00:25:37.040
This idea that communities are living systems, basically.

00:25:37.220 --> 00:25:41.030
They produce themselves, and the more that they can reliably produce

00:25:41.170 --> 00:25:46.440
themselves within the assurance of the holdfast, like Erin said

00:25:46.440 --> 00:25:49.440
, the better they can learn and adapt.

00:25:49.550 --> 00:25:52.320
If we, as technologists, give communities tools to protect

00:25:52.360 --> 00:25:55.900
themselves against assault, but also to learn and adapt to the

00:25:55.900 --> 00:26:00.040
broader environment, we cultivate the conditions for a world where many

00:26:00.040 --> 00:26:00.890
worlds can fit.

00:26:03.550 --> 00:26:06.790
We're working on really enormous, important, and very particular

00:26:06.880 --> 00:26:08.770
problems here, and it can be hard, but we are

00:26:08.770 --> 00:26:10.160
so much more powerful together.

00:26:10.330 --> 00:26:12.720
So let's find each other.

00:26:13.030 --> 00:26:13.600
Thank you.

00:26:23.860 --> 00:26:24.630
Thank you so much, Mary.

00:26:24.640 --> 00:26:25.760
That was a beautiful talk.

00:26:25.900 --> 00:26:27.910
We have some time for questions.

00:26:27.920 --> 00:26:28.800
Yes.

00:26:28.950 --> 00:26:30.400
Oh, sorry, wait.

00:26:30.400 --> 00:26:32.680
I must give this to you so they can hear you in

00:26:32.680 --> 00:26:33.400
the streaming.

00:26:33.630 --> 00:26:38.050
Yeah, so during the pandemic, a lot of us spent

00:26:38.390 --> 00:26:42.160
a lot of time on the computer, and there were a

00:26:42.160 --> 00:26:47.360
lot of musicians that went to Discord and found new collaborations with

00:26:47.360 --> 00:26:48.160
each other.

00:26:48.340 --> 00:26:51.760
This was really important for me because I didn't really have

00:26:51.760 --> 00:26:54.150
local community that partook in the same kind of music that

00:26:54.170 --> 00:26:56.650
I liked, so it completely changed my life as an artist

00:26:56.650 --> 00:26:56.880
.

00:26:56.920 --> 00:27:00.560
I know there are some significant technical boundaries with implementing multimedia support

00:27:00.560 --> 00:27:02.510
, but do you have any plans for VC in the future

00:27:02.510 --> 00:27:02.710
?

00:27:02.900 --> 00:27:05.710
Because I feel like that would unlock a whole new community of

00:27:05.710 --> 00:27:09.610
other people that communicate via sonics where words don't really

00:27:09.610 --> 00:27:11.030
serve the same purpose.

00:27:12.680 --> 00:27:14.160
I agree it's a really important problem.

00:27:14.160 --> 00:27:18.720
It's not at the center of what we're trying to

00:27:18.720 --> 00:27:19.200
do right now.

00:27:19.420 --> 00:27:25.760
And I guess I'm hoping to see that we can,

00:27:25.830 --> 00:27:29.250
as a community, come up with solutions for this and share

00:27:29.250 --> 00:27:35.640
resources around this because, yeah, I think these are tools

00:27:35.640 --> 00:27:38.210
that we need and it makes sense to have it on protocol

00:27:38.210 --> 00:27:38.400
.

00:27:41.380 --> 00:27:42.150
Hopefully we can get there.

00:27:42.380 --> 00:27:43.110
Awesome.

00:27:43.120 --> 00:27:43.440
Thank you.

00:27:43.630 --> 00:27:53.200
Thanks for the inspiring

00:27:53.200 --> 00:27:54.160
talk.

00:27:54.160 --> 00:28:00.750
You mentioned in passing this kind of aspiration to resist monopolies

00:28:00.850 --> 00:28:04.300
through cooperative sort of federation, and I wonder if you

00:28:04.300 --> 00:28:06.400
had any more thoughts on like, yeah, just expanding on

00:28:06.400 --> 00:28:07.920
that a little and where your head's at with that.

00:28:11.120 --> 00:28:13.720
I think, yeah, I guess like it's interesting,

00:28:13.910 --> 00:28:18.720
like what in one of Paul's essays, like talking about

00:28:18.720 --> 00:28:24.870
lexicons as a tool for negotiating, like the governance

00:28:24.870 --> 00:28:27.280
of like how interoperability works.

00:28:28.180 --> 00:28:34.890
And yeah, like I feel like these kind of emerging organizations

00:28:34.890 --> 00:28:38.830
like lexicon community, like are going to become more

00:28:38.900 --> 00:28:42.000
and more important because to me, like our biggest shared resource

00:28:42.270 --> 00:28:44.800
is the kind of shared data on the protocol.

00:28:44.990 --> 00:28:49.150
And so we could end up in a place where everyone's

00:28:49.150 --> 00:28:54.000
trying to keep their cards close to their chest to gain leverage

00:28:54.070 --> 00:28:57.670
and I guess the point that I really wanted to make is

00:28:57.890 --> 00:29:01.840
that we're all small fish and there are some really big

00:29:01.840 --> 00:29:06.140
sharks and we need to destroy that world.

00:29:06.390 --> 00:29:09.460
We need to like move way past that world, you know

00:29:09.480 --> 00:29:09.520
, we need to like move way past that world, you

00:29:09.520 --> 00:29:12.860
know, so we only do that by working together, by

00:29:12.870 --> 00:29:16.070
sharing our resources, this is like the theory of change of

00:29:16.330 --> 00:29:18.000
like cooperative businesses.

00:29:18.820 --> 00:29:25.920
So yeah, I think like community efforts to like really actively

00:29:25.920 --> 00:29:29.480
make space to coordinate with each other.

00:29:29.940 --> 00:29:32.400
Like that's a social work we need to do.

00:29:32.590 --> 00:29:37.360
Thank you so much, Mary.

00:29:37.440 --> 00:29:40.150
I'd like to invite Victoria up here.

00:29:40.240 --> 00:29:40.950
Oh, yes, please.

00:29:41.010 --> 00:29:42.640
A round of applause.

00:29:42.830 --> 00:29:44.730
Thank you.
